## Remote Functions

### Overview

Remote Functions allow you to call server-side functions directly from Svelte components using `await`. They replace the need for API routes for many use cases.

### Defining Remote Functions

Create `.remote.ts` or `.remote.js` files in your routes directory:

```typescript
// src/routes/posts/data.remote.ts
import { query, command } from "$app/server";
import * as v from "valibot";
import { db } from "$lib/server/db";
import * as table from "$lib/server/db/schema";

// Query function - for reading data
export const getPosts = query(async () => {
  const posts = await db.select().from(table.posts);
  return posts;
});

// Query with validation
export const getPost = query(
  v.string(), // Input validation schema
  async (slug) => {
    const [post] = await db
      .select()
      .from(table.posts)
      .where(eq(table.posts.slug, slug));
    return post;
  }
);

// Command function - for mutations
export const createPost = command(
  v.object({
    title: v.string(),
    content: v.string(),
  }),
  async (data) => {
    await db.insert(table.posts).values(data);
  }
);
```

### Using Remote Functions in Components

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { getPosts, createPost } from './data.remote';
</script>

<!-- Using await directly -->
<ul>
  {#each await getPosts() as post}
    <li>{post.title}</li>
  {/each}
</ul>

<!-- Using with loading/error states -->
<script lang="ts">
  const postsQuery = getPosts();
</script>

{#if postsQuery.error}
  <p>Error loading posts</p>
{:else if postsQuery.loading}
  <p>Loading...</p>
{:else}
  <ul>
    {#each postsQuery.current as post}
      <li>{post.title}</li>
    {/each}
  </ul>
{/if}
```

### Handling Form Submissions with Remote Functions

Use `command` functions for form submissions. Handle form data in your component:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
	import { createPost } from './data.remote';

	let title = $state('');
	let content = $state('');
	let loading = $state(false);
	let error = $state<string | null>(null);
	let success = $state(false);

	async function handleSubmit() {
		loading = true;
		error = null;
		try {
			await createPost({ title, content });
			success = true;
			title = '';
			content = '';
		} catch (e) {
			error = e instanceof Error ? e.message : 'An error occurred';
		} finally {
			loading = false;
		}
	}
</script>

<form
	onsubmit={(e) => {
		e.preventDefault();
		handleSubmit();
	}}
>
	<input bind:value={title} placeholder="Title" />
	<textarea bind:value={content} placeholder="Content" />
	<button type="submit" disabled={loading}>
		{loading ? 'Creating...' : 'Create Post'}
	</button>
</form>

{#if error}
	<p style="color: red">{error}</p>
{/if}

{#if success}
	<p>Post created successfully!</p>
{/if}
```

### Best Practices

1. **Use `query` for read operations** - Automatically cached and optimized
2. **Use `command` for write operations** - Mutations that change data, including form submissions
3. **Always validate inputs** - Use Valibot schemas for type safety
4. **Prefer Remote Functions over API routes** - Simpler and more type-safe
5. **Use `query.batch` for multiple queries** - Automatically batches requests
6. **Handle errors in components** - Wrap command calls in try-catch blocks
7. **Use loading states** - Provide feedback during async operations

